    "experimental_design_for_optimization": {
        "pellets_preparation": "Drug loading was done in a conventional coating pan. Sugar pellets (50-60#) were coated by alternating cycles of spraying binder solution (Sucrose and HPMC 032_E5 in purified water) and drug powder (Metoprolol succinate, Aerosil, Sucrose) to achieve desired loading. Drug-loaded pellets were dried and sifted. They were then coated with polymer solutions (Surelease, Ethyl cellulose, Kollicoat SR 30D) using a Fluidised Bed Coater (Wurster bottom spray) to achieve different coating levels (7.5%, 10%, 12.5%, 15%). Coated pellets were sifted.",
        "tablets_preparation": "MUPS tablets were prepared by direct compression. Coated pellets were mixed with excipients (MCC pH102, Aerosil, Magnesium stearate, Lubritab) in a Double cone blender and compressed using an 8-station tablet compression machine (Karnavati Mini Press II).",
        "results": "Formulation 032_F10 (pellets with 7.5% Kollicoat SR 30D coating) was found to be the best pellet formulation. Formulation 032_T4 (tablets with 15% Lubritab) was found to be the most promising MUPS formulation with acceptable physicochemical properties and dissolution profile similar to the innovator product.",
        "equation_absorbance": "Drug release was analyzed by UV Spectrophotometric method at a wavelength of 223 nm.\\nWater content by K.F. titration: % Water Content = (V × F × 100) / W, where V = Volume of K.F. reagent, F = Factor for K.F. reagent, W = Weight of sample in grams.\\nSimilarity factor (f2) and dissimilarity factor (f1) were calculated to compare dissolution profiles."
    },
